name: Подмосковные вечера
comments: Contrary to credits given for the Kenny Ball version, this is not a traditional folk song. Originally written in 1955 as "Ленинградские вечера" ("Leningradskie vechera"), the title was changed in 1956, with accompanying changes in the lyrics, to "Подмосковные вечера" ("Podmoskovnye vechera", in English: "Moscow Suburban Evenings"). It was first sung by Vladimir Troshin for a film on the 1956 Spartakiad sports festival.

name: Pugni chiusi
comments: Dall'Aglio might have been the sole author of the music. According to his own account, Dall'Aglio wrote the song but couldn't sign it with his name as he wasn't a member of SIAE (Italian Society of Authors and Editors). Therefore, he sold his rights to Gianco who, in turn, had to pay his share of royalties to Dall'Aglio. Years later, Dall'Aglio decided to tell his version of the story after he heard Gianco saying: "Pugni chiusi is the best song I've written". Ironically, the authors (whether real or fake) were accused of plagiarism already upon the release of the song: according to many music critics and experts, Pugni chiusi sounded "too similar" to When a Man Loves a Woman , although Dall'Oglio claimed that his main source of inspiration had been Georgia on My Mind .

name: Everybody Loves Saturday Night
comments: Probably of African West Coast origin. From Jim Moran's blog: "The song existed well before the 1950s and 70s curfews that urban/internet legends suggest created the song. The original Nigerian song apparently was only a fragment of a forgotten older piece. It was Trinidadian calypso singer Aldwyn Roberts "Lord Kitchener" who popularized it in Britain in the late 1940s by repeating the song's one line over and over in different languages - hence the association of this African song with Caribbean rhythms and styles."

name: Come All You Fair and Tender Ladies
comments: American folk ballad from the Appalachians.  Cecil Sharp collected 18 versions of this ballad between 1916 and 1918 and published in his book "English Folk-Songs from the Southern Appalachians".  It is number 451 in the Roud Folk Song Index. The song is also known as "Sparrow", "Tiny Sparrow" and "Little Sparrow". Roscoe Holcomb deleted the opening two verses and recorded it in 1965 as "Willow Tree", which has led to subsequent cover performances. Lyrics start off - "Come all ye fair and tender ladies, Take warning how you court your men...", later in song lyrics are "I wish I was a little sparrow and I had wings to fly so high..." Not to be confused with Dolly Parton's Little Sparrow that starts off "Little sparrow, little sparrow, precious fragile little thing..."
